            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Farhan Kozlov\u2019s story is one of spice routes and fault lines, born in Tashkent to an Uzbek mother and a Russian engineer father. His youth was steeped in the aromas of plov and freshly baked non from his grandmother\u2019s kitchen, set against the crumbling backdrop of the late Soviet Union. This dual heritage gave him a unique palate and a sense of being perpetually between worlds, a feeling that would later define his culinary philosophy.\n\nThe economic chaos of the post-Soviet 90s propelled him outward. Seeing food as a universal language, he pursued a graduate degree in Hospitality Management in Switzerland. There, he honed classical French techniques in punishing kitchens, but found himself yearning for the bold, honest flavors of his childhood. He realized his future wasn't in recreating European cuisine, but in reinventing his own. San Francisco, with its history of fusion and innovation, became his destination.\n\nArriving in his late twenties, Farhan worked his way up through the city\u2019s demanding restaurant scene. The key turning point came when he met his business partner, a savvy front-of-house manager who believed in his vision. Together, they secured funding and opened \"Samarkand,\" their Hayes Valley restaurant. It was a risk\u2014a fine-dining take on Silk Road cuisine using Californian ingredients\u2014but it found a rapt audience.\n\nNow 53, Farhan\u2019s life revolves around the restaurant. A short-lived marriage in his thirties dissolved under the pressure of 16-hour days; his staff is now his family. His 5.8-mile drive from his quiet Inner Sunset home to the vibrant energy of Hayes Valley is a daily ritual of mental preparation. Mornings are for visiting farmers' markets, evenings for orchestrating service, a whirlwind of heat, orders, and creation. He lives comfortably, his income a testament to the relentless work he\u2019s poured into his craft.\n\nFarhan\u2019s connection to San Francisco is profound; it\u2019s the city that gave his bicultural identity a place to flourish. His aspiration is no longer just about accolades, but about legacy. He dreams of writing a definitive cookbook on modern Central Asian food and mentoring a young chef to eventually take his place. He quietly hopes to find a partner to share the calmer years ahead, someone who understands that his love language will always be a perfectly seasoned dish, served with heart."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being seven, small enough to hide in the folds of his grandmother\u2019s apron in their Tashkent kitchen. He\u2019d watch her strong, flour-dusted hands press the *chekich* stamp into the center of the non dough, a sacred, floral seal. The smell of the raw dough and the intense heat from the tandoor felt like the safest place on earth. It wasn't just bread; it was a promise of nourishment and love. That moment cemented his belief that food\u2019s most vital ingredient is memory.\n\n2.\nIn a gleaming Swiss kitchen, around age 24, he stared at his reflection in a perfectly reduced demi-glace. He\u2019d just finished plating a fillet of sole, each component placed with tweezer-like precision. It was technically flawless, praised by the chef, yet it felt utterly foreign to him. There was no soul, no echo of his grandmother\u2019s laughter or the fire of dill and coriander. That cold, perfect plate made him realize he couldn't just borrow a culinary language; he had to speak his own.\n\n3.\nHe was 32, walking through the Ferry Plaza Farmers Market, feeling the familiar immigrant ache of being adrift. Then he saw them: Blenheim apricots, small and intensely fragrant. They weren\u2019t the same as the ones dried on Tashkent rooftops, but they had the same sun-drenched soul. Holding one, he suddenly saw his future: Uzbek flavors, Californian terroir. The city wasn't a place of exile; it was a new silk road. He felt, for the first time, a sense of arrival.\n\n4.\nIt was six months after Samarkand opened. Exhausted after service, he leaned against the kitchen doorframe, listening to the dining room's hum. A woman at a nearby table told her companion, \u201cIt tastes like a story I\u2019ve never heard but somehow already know.\u201d Tears pricked his eyes. The years of loneliness, the punishing hours, the failed marriage\u2014it all coalesced into that single sentence of validation. His food was speaking for him. His bicultural heart had finally been understood.\n\n5.\nJust last week, after the last staff member left, he sat alone at table seven with a glass of tea. The chairs were stacked, the kitchen silent. He ran a hand over the polished wood, the restaurant breathing around him like a sleeping child he had raised. He had built this world from spice and fire. The profound satisfaction was tinged with a quiet question, wondering who he might one day get to share this peaceful silence with. The thought wasn't sad, just\u2026 hopeful."
